      ]} />

      <header class="mb-10">
        <p class="mb-3 text-sm font-medium uppercase tracking-widest text-primary">Guide</p>
        <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight sm:text-4xl lg:text-5xl">{title}</h1>
        <p class="mt-4 text-lg text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed">{description}</p>
        <div class="mt-4 flex items-center gap-4 text-sm text-muted-foreground">
          <time datetime={publishDate}>March 28, 2026</time>
          <span>&middot;</span>
          <span>12 min read</span>
        </div>
      </header>

      <div class="prose prose-invert max-w-none space-y-6 text-base leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground [&_h2]:text-foreground [&_h2]:text-2xl [&_h2]:font-bold [&_h2]:mt-10 [&_h2]:mb-4 [&_h3]:text-foreground [&_h3]:text-xl [&_h3]:font-semibold [&_h3]:mt-8 [&_h3]:mb-3 [&_strong]:text-foreground [&_a]:text-primary [&_a]:underline [&_a:hover]:text-foreground">

        <h2>How Nicotine Pouches Work</h2>
        <p>
          <strong>Nicotine pouches are small white sachets that contain nicotine, plant-based fibres, flavourings, and other ingredients designed for oral delivery</strong>. You place one between your upper lip and gum, and the nicotine absorbs through the mucous membrane. It takes about 2 to 5 minutes to feel the first effects, with nicotine delivery peaking around 5 to 10 minutes. All pouches sold in the EU comply with tobacco product regulations (TPD 2014/40/EU) for safety, quality, and labelling.
        </p>
        <p>
          Unlike traditional <a href="/blog/nicotine-pouches-vs-snus">snus</a> (which contains tobacco), modern nicotine
          pouches are tobacco-free. They're completely white, discreet, and don't stain your teeth. You keep the pouch in
          for 15-45 minutes, then pop it out and bin it. Think of it as a slow-release nicotine delivery system with no
          smoke, no combustion, no ash.
        </p>

        <h2>Choosing Your Strength: The Tier System</h2>
        <p>
          This is the most important decision you'll make. Get the strength wrong, and you'll either be disappointed
          (too weak) or uncomfortably buzzed (too strong).
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong><a href="/products/strength/mild">Mild (2-4 mg per pouch)</a></strong> — For complete beginners or
          people who want a light kick. Good for testing whether you even like nicotine before committing to stronger options.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong><a href="/products/strength/regular">Regular (4-8 mg per pouch)</a></strong> — The sweet spot for most
          people transitioning from cigarettes. A noticeable buzz without being overwhelming. Most popular brands like
          <a href="/brands/zyn">ZYN</a> and <a href="/brands/velo">VELO</a> sell their core products in this range.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong><a href="/products/strength/strong">Strong (8-12 mg per pouch)</a></strong> — For people with moderate
          nicotine tolerance. If you smoke a pack a day or more, this is where you'll probably land.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong><a href="/products/strength/extra-strong">Extra Strong (12-20 mg per pouch)</a></strong> — Designed
          for heavy users. These hit hard and fast. Not for newbies.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong><a href="/products/strength/super-strong">Extreme (20+ mg per pouch)</a></strong> — Some brands push
          up to 30+ mg per pouch. These cater to seasoned nicotine users who've built serious tolerance.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>How to choose:</strong> Start lower than you think you need. The nicotine hits differently depending
          on the brand too — some brands have higher moisture and deliver more smoothly and quickly. Read our
          <a href="/blog/how-to-choose-your-strength">strength guide</a> for the full breakdown.
        </p>

        <h2>Understanding Formats: Slim vs Mini vs Normal</h2>
        <p>
          <strong>Slim</strong> — The standard size for most brands. Sits comfortably between your lip and gum. Most
          popular format in Europe.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Mini</strong> — Noticeably smaller and more discreet. Ideal if you want something nearly invisible.
          ZYN offers a lot of options in mini format.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Normal (or "Full")</strong> — Thicker and larger, holds more material and delivers a bigger nicotine
          boost. Less common now as most modern brands have standardized on slim.
        </p>

        <h2>Flavour Categories Explained</h2>
        <p>
          <strong><a href="/products/flavor/mint">Mint and Menthol</a></strong> — The most popular category. Clean,
          fresh, and genuinely pleasant. Ranges from subtle spearmint to aggressive peppermint.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong><a href="/products/flavor/berry">Fruit and Berry</a></strong> — Covers everything from strawberry to
          watermelon to mixed berry. Quality varies — some taste artificial, others surprisingly natural.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong><a href="/products/flavor/citrus">Citrus</a></strong> — Lemon, lime, grapefruit, orange. Zesty and
          refreshing. Less heavy than berry flavours.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong><a href="/products/flavor/coffee">Coffee and Tobacco</a></strong> — For purists who want something
          resembling snus or traditional tobacco products. Coffee flavours give a warm, earthy vibe.
        </p>

        <h2>Top Brands for European Buyers</h2>
        <p>
          <strong><a href="/brands/zyn">ZYN</a></strong> — The market leader. Consistent, well-made, available everywhere
          in Europe. Huge range of flavours and strengths. Pouches are drier than competitors, meaning slower nicotine
          release — good if you want a steady buzz. Their "Citrus" and "Cool Mint" are reliable crowd-pleasers.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong><a href="/brands/velo">VELO</a></strong> — Premium option with excellent build quality. Pouches are
          softer and more moist than ZYN, so the nicotine and flavour hit faster. Wild flavour combinations available.
          Slightly pricier but many people think it's worth it.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong><a href="/brands/loop">Loop</a></strong> — The Scandinavian innovator with patented InstantRush
          technology — faster and stronger initial nicotine release, followed by a longer sustained experience.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong><a href="/brands/skruf">Skruf</a></strong> — A Swedish brand with serious heritage. Dependable and
          popular in Scandinavia. Strong minty flavours and straightforward branding.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong><a href="/brands/helwit">HELWIT</a></strong> — A newer European brand focusing on natural ingredients
          and sustainable packaging. More "natural" tasting than mass-market brands.
        </p>

        <h2>EU Regulations: What You Need to Know</h2>
        <p>
          Nicotine pouches are not classified as tobacco products under EU law, which means individual member states make
          their own rules. This has led to a patchwork of regulations.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Germany and Belgium</strong> — Commercial sales are banned in both countries. Belgium enforces a complete ban including import; Germany bans domestic sale but personal import from other EU countries may be tolerated in small quantities — check current customs guidance before ordering.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Denmark</strong> — Strict new rules as of April 2026: only tobacco and menthol flavours allowed,
          nicotine capped at 9 mg per pouch, and excise taxes added.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Austria</strong> — Classified as controlled adult nicotine products and must be sold through licensed
          tobacconists only. Excise taxes apply.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>France</strong> — Banned commercial sale of nicotine pouches in February 2025. An additional decree set for April 2026 was temporarily suspended by the French Council of State, pending a final ruling expected June 2026. Commercial sales remain prohibited under existing French public health law.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>UK</strong> (post-Brexit) — Largely unregulated. No major restrictions. Age restrictions (18+) apply.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Scandinavia</strong> (Sweden, Norway) — Generally permissive. These countries see nicotine pouches as
          a harm-reduction tool. No major restrictions yet.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Luxembourg</strong> — Effectively banned as of November 2025, when Bill 8333 capped nicotine at 0.048 mg per pouch (a de facto prohibition) and banned flavourings in nicotine products.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Coming soon: EU-wide rules.</strong> The Tobacco Products Directive 3 (TPD3) is expected mid-2026, with full implementation around 2028. It will likely introduce EU-wide nicotine content limits, packaging standards, and sales channel controls for nicotine pouches. This will replace the current country-by-country patchwork.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Before buying online:</strong> Check your country's current status, as regulations change quickly. If
          you're in a banned/restricted country, cross-border shipping likely won't work. Always look for reputable
          sellers with age verification.
        </p>

        <h2>How to Store Your Pouches</h2>
        <p>
          <strong>Keep them cool and dry.</strong> Room temperature (18-22 C) is ideal. Heat speeds up degradation.
          Always seal the tin tightly — exposure to air dries them out within days.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Consider the fridge.</strong> If you're a light user and pouches sit around for weeks, keeping the tin
          sealed in the fridge extends freshness by 2-3 months. Don't freeze — it changes the texture.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Shelf life:</strong> Unopened cans last 12-24 months. Once opened, enjoy them within 30-60 days for
          peak freshness.
        </p>

        <h2>How Much Should You Pay?</h2>
        <p>
          <strong>Retail shops</strong> (convenience stores, petrol stations): 5-8 EUR per can. Most expensive.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Online retailers</strong> (within Europe): 2.50-4 EUR per can. Cheapest option when buying in bulk.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>The maths:</strong> If you use one can per week (25 pouches typically), that's 10-40 EUR per month
          depending on where and what you buy. Compare that to cigarettes (7-10 EUR per pack in most of Europe) and
          it's competitive or cheaper, especially online.
        </p>

        <h2>FAQ</h2>
        <h3>Are nicotine pouches safer than cigarettes?</h3>
        <p>
          They're not risk-free (nicotine is addictive), but they eliminate combustion, tar, and most carcinogens in
          smoke. Most harm reduction experts see them as significantly lower-risk than smoking.
        </p>

        <h3>How long does one pouch last?</h3>
        <p>
          15-45 minutes, depending on the brand, strength, and your preference. ZYN tends to last longer (steadier
          release). VELO hits hard and fades faster. Read our
          <a href="/blog/how-long-do-nicotine-pouches-last">detailed duration guide</a>.
        </p>

        <h3>What's the difference between nicotine pouches and snus?</h3>
        <p>
          Snus contains tobacco leaf; nicotine pouches don't. Both deliver nicotine through the gum line, but snus
          tastes different (earthier, more complex). Pouches are whiter, cleaner, easier to travel with. Read our
          <a href="/blog/nicotine-pouches-vs-snus">full comparison</a>.
        </p>

        <h3>Can I use them at work without anyone noticing?</h3>
        <p>
          Completely discreet if you use mini pouches. Nobody can tell you're using them — no smell, no visible smoke,
          no spitting. They're great for offices.
        </p>
      </div>

